trigger types:
- manual trigger
- single branch trigger
- multi-branch trigger (include & exclude)
- path based trigger (inlcude & exclude)
- PR based trigger
- scheduled triggger
- resources trigger (CI completed then run CD pipeline)


trigger: none                                  # manual trigger

- Disables automatic pipeline execution.
- Pipeline runs only when manually triggered.
- Commonly used for production deployments.

trigger:                                      # Single Branch trigger  
- main

- Runs pipeline whenever code is pushed to main branch.
- Implements Continuous Integration (CI).
- Automatically validates code changes.

trigger:                                       # Multi-branch trigger 
  branches:
    include:
    - main
    - develop
    - release/*
    exclue:
    - feature/*                                #Prevents pipeline execution on specific branches.

- Controls which branches can trigger pipeline.
- Allows multiple branches.
- Improves control.
- Useful for release strategy.

trigger:                                       # Path based trigger (inlcude & exclude)
  paths:
    include:
    - src/*
    exclude:
    - README.md
    - docs/*

- Triggers pipeline only if specific files/folders change.
- Useful for monorepos.
- Reduces pipeline executions.
- Ignores changes in specific files/folders.
- Common for documentation changes.


pr:                                             # Pull Request is created or updated.
- main


Purpose
- Triggers pipeline only if specific files/folders change.
- Useful for monorepos.
- Reduces pipeline executions.
- Saves build time.
- Improves efficiency.

schedules:
- cron: "0 2 * * *"

resources:
  pipelines:
  - pipelin*: BuildPipeline
    source: Build
    trigger: true

- Automatically starts pipeline when another pipeline completes successfully.
- Removes need for manual execution.
- Enables chained pipelines.
- Supports automated releases.

